article.headline: Career highs from Jones, Taylor add up to Rockers win
article.linkText: Rockers win in Indiana to break road losing streak
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A 1-2 offensive punch and an overall
defensive effort by the Cleveland Rockers against Indiana rookie
Tamika Catchings paid off Saturday night.

	   Merlakia Jones had career-highs of 27 points and 11 field goals
as the Rockers defeated the Fever 79-68.

	   Penny Taylor added 20 points as Cleveland (2-4) recorded its
first road victory of the season and snapped a three-game losing
streak. Chasity Melvin was the only other Cleveland player in
double figures with 10 points.

	   Tamika Catchings led Indiana (4-4) with 23 points, but scored
only six in the second half when the league's third-leading scorer
hit just 1-of-7 shots from the field.

	   "We showed her a lot of attention. We made a real point (at
halftime) to recognize her, and we brought a lot of people at her.
She's that good a player,'' Cleveland coach Dan Hughes said of the
former Tennessee star, who brought a 19.6 scoring average into the
game.

	   Jones, who missed just two shots from the field, had 17 points
in the second half when Cleveland outscored the Fever 47-35.

	   "That's a well as I've seen her play offensively,'' Hughes said
of Jones, in her sixth WNBA season and her fourth with Hughes as
her coach. "Her ability to make good decisions with the basketball
was as good as I've ever seen her play.''

	   "I wasn't worried about the number of points that I scored. I
just wanted to come out and be aggressive,'' Jones said. "It was a
great team win. Everybody stepped up.''

	   Cleveland, which trailed most of the first half and 33-32 at the
break, took the lead for good at 41-39 on a short jumper by Ann
Wauters.

	   The Rockers, who shot 56 percent from the field, helped
themselves by hitting 21-of-24 free throws. The Rockers also
outrebounded Indiana, which went into the game leading the league
in defensive and overall rebounding percentage.

	   A seven-point run gave Cleveland a 60-49 lead with 8:35
remaining. Melvin started the run by hitting two free throws with
11:10 to play. Taylor then made one of two free throws, Melvin hit
a layup and Tracy Henderson's short jumper ended the run.

	   The Fever never drew closer than seven points again. Indiana
managed to cut it's deficit to 67-59 with 4:52 remaining. Jones
answered by hitting a 3-pointer just as the 30-second shot clock
was going off. The Rockers then went on to take their biggest lead
of the night at 79-66 on a free throw by Jennifer Rizzotti's with
17 seconds remaining.

	   "The second half we didn't move the ball. Then we started
looking to Tamika. That slowed down our offense,'' Indiana coach
Nell Fortune said. "People just have to step up. We're a much
better team when we move the ball around. We seemed to lose our
confidence in the second half."
